V{{Infobox philosopher\u000a|region           = \u000a|era              = \u000a|color            = lightsteelblue\u000a|image       =\u000a|image_size       =\u000a|caption    =\u000a|name             = Susanna Schellenberg\u000a|birth_date       = \u000a|birth_place      = \u000a|death_date       =\u000a|school_tradition = \u000a|main_interests   = [[epistemology]], [[philosophy of mind]], [[perception]], [[philosophy of language]],\u000a|notable_ideas    = \u000a|institutions     = [[Rutgers University]], [[Australian National University]]\u000a|influences       = [[Gottlob Frege]], [[Aristotle]]\u000a|influenced       =\u000a|signature        =\u000a}}\u000a'''Susanna Schellenberg''' is a philosopher specializing in epistemology, philosophy of mind, and philosophy of language.<ref name=bio>{{cite web|title=Schellenberg, Susanna|url=http://philosophy.rutgers.edu/people/faculty/627-schellenberg-susanna|publisher=Rutgers|accessdate=29 May 2013}}</ref><ref name=leiter>{{cite web|last=Leiter|first=Brian|title=Rutgers Raids the ANU: Schaffer, Schellenberg to New Brunswick in 2011|url=http://leiterreports.typepad.com/blog/2009/11/rutgers-raids-the-anu-schaffer-schellenberg-to-new-brunswick-in-2011.html|publisher=Leiter Reports|accessdate=29 May 2013}}</ref><ref name=tar>{{cite web|last=Weatherson|first=Brian|title=Rutgers News|url=http://tar.weatherson.org/2009/11/20/rutgers-news/|publisher=Thoughts, Arguments, and Rants}}</ref>    She is best known for her work on perceptual experience, evidence, capacities, mental content, and imagination. She is professor of philosophy at [[Rutgers University]], where she holds a secondary appointment at the Rutgers Center for Cognitive Science.<ref name=apacsw>{{cite web|last=DesAutels|first=Peggy|title=Susanna Schellenberg: October 2013|url=http://www.apaonlinecsw.org/home/woman_philosopher/susannaschellenbergoctober2013|work=Highlighted Philosophers|publisher=American Philosophical Association|accessdate=15 October 2013}}</ref><ref name=affiliate>{{cite web|title=Affiliates|url=http://ruccs.rutgers.edu/ruccs/index.php/people/affiliates|publisher=Rutgers|accessdate=29 May 2013}}</ref>  In 2016, Schellenberg was awarded the Friedrich Wilhelm Bessel Research Award of the Humboldt Foundation. Her work has been published in journals such as [[Noûs]], [[The Journal of Philosophy]], [[Mind]], and [[Philosophy and Phenomenological Research]].<ref name=philpapers>{{cite web|title=Works by Susanna Schellenberg|url=http://philpapers.org/s/Susanna%20Schellenberg|publisher=Phil Papers|accessdate=29 May 2013}}</ref>\u000a\u000a==Education and employment==\u000aSchellenberg was born in Beirut, Lebanon, and raised in Lebanon, Pakistan, and Switzerland.<ref name=3am>{{cite web|last=Marshall|first=Richard|title=epistemic forces and perception|url=http://www.3ammagazine.com/3am/epistemic-forces-and-perception/|publisher=3:AM Magazine|accessdate=15 October 2013}}</ref>  After having received a mathematical-scientific Matura (Typus C) from the Gymnasium Köniz-Lebermatt, Switzerland, she studied mathematics, economics, philosophy, and history at the Universität Basel, Université Paris I Panthéone-Sorbonne, Johann-Wolfgang Goethe Universität, and Oxford University.<ref name=bio/><ref name=3am/><ref name=cv>{{cite web|last=Schellenberg|first=Susanna|title=Curriculum Vitae|url=http://www.susannaschellenberg.org/file/CV_files/CV-SusannaSchellenberg.pdf}}</ref> She received a doctorate in philosophy from the [[University of Pittsburgh]] in 2007, where her thesis dealt with conceptual content and inference.<ref name=bio/><ref name=upitt>{{cite web|title=Graduate Placement|url=http://www.philosophy.pitt.edu/graduate/placement.php|publisher=University of Pittsburgh}}</ref>\u000a\u000aSchellenberg held a [[Andrew W. Mellon Foundation|Mellon postdoctoral fellowship]] at the [[University of Toronto]] from 2006 to 2008 which was curtailed when she chose to move to a postdoctoral position at the [[Australian National University]], where she subsequently became an assistant professor in 2008, and an associate professor in 2010.<ref name=apacsw/> Schellenberg was the first woman to hold a permanent academic appointment in Philosophy at the Australia National University's Research School of Social Sciences.<ref name=apacsw/> In 2011, Schellenberg moved to [[Rutgers University]], as an associate professor in the Department of Philosophy with a secondary appointment at Rutgers Center for Cognitive Science.<ref name=apacsw/> [[Brian Weatherson]] and [[Jonathan L. Kvanvig]] regarded Schellenberg's move to Rutgers as buttressing Rutgers' reputation as having one of the pre-eminent epistemology departments in the world.<ref name=tar/><ref name=certaindoubts>{{cite web|last=Kvanvig|first=Jonathan|title=Adding to Rutgers Strength in Epistemology|url=http://certaindoubts.com/?p=1557|publisher=Certain Doubts|accessdate=29 May 2013}}</ref>\u000a\u000a==Research areas==\u000aSchellenberg's work has centered around developing a comprehensive account of the epistemological and phenomenological role of perception.<ref name=apacsw/> Her view shows how the epistemic force of experience is grounded in employing perceptual capacities that we possess by virtue of being perceivers<ref name=apacsw/>  Schellenberg has also developed an account of the nature of perceptual content that suggests a new way to understand singular modes of presentation, arguing that perceptual experience is at root both relational and representational.<ref name=apacsw/>  In addition to her main areas of interest, Schellenberg has also written papers on topics such as inferential semantics, the philosophy of [[Gottlob Frege]], and imagination.<ref name=apacsw/><ref name=3am/>  Much of Schellenberg's work to-date has focused on reconcilling apparently contradictory viewpoints on topics in the [[philosophy of mind]].<ref name=tar/>\u000a\u000a==Publications==\u000aSchellenberg has published a number of peer-reviewed papers in journals such as [[The Journal of Philosophy]], [[Mind]], [[Noûs]], and [[Philosophy and Phenomenological Research]].<ref name=cv/> She has also contributed five book chapters, including chapters about perceptual experience, externalism and hallucination, and [[Wilfrid Sellars|Sellarsian perspectives]] on perception.<ref name=cv/>\u000a\u000a==References==\u000a{{reflist}}\u000a\u000a==External links==\u000a*[http://philpapers.org/profile/1099 Susanna Schellenberg on PhilPapers]\u000a*[http://www.susannaschellenberg.org/file/Home.html Susanna Schellenberg website]\u000a\u000a\u000a{{DEFAULTSORT:Schellenberg, Susanna}}\u000a[[Category:Living people]]\u000a[[Category:Rutgers University faculty]]\u000a[[Category:Philosophers of mind]]\u000a[[Category:University of Pittsburgh alumni]]\u000a[[Category:Women philosophers]]\u000a[[Category:Epistemologists]]\u000a[[Category:Philosophers of language]]\u000a[[Category:21st-century philosophers]]\u000a[[Category:1974 births]]
